      <hedline>
        <hl1>Write 100 Times: Give Homework</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nancy Smiler Levinson letter, commenting on Oct 10 article, says developing a love for reading in children can allay fears that they might not be getting enough homework; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As Homework Load Grows, One District Says 'Enough' '' (front page, Oct. 10):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As Homework Load Grows, One District Says 'Enough' '' (front page, Oct. 10):</p>
        <p>Families concerned with the amount of homework might be reminded that children can make immeasurable gains from reading for pleasure. A visit to a library or a children's bookstore has made a great many people lifelong readers and learners. Getting comfortable with a good novel or biography for the joy of it can advance a child in knowledge, use of language, moral decision-making and in understanding one's own feelings, as well as one's place in the world.</p>
        <p>NANCY SMILER LEVINSON  Beverly Hills, Calif., Oct. 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
